        ],
        [
          "Classification",
          "Intelligent Tutoring System",
          "Correctedness of next question",
          "Correct (1) vs Incorrect (0)",
          "4417 ASSISTments2009 learners, 19917 ASSISTments2012 learners, 333 Statics Learners, 2000 Simulated Learners",
          "ASSISTments, Statics",
          "Sequence of Answers",
          "[Confounding Variables Matrix, Sequence of Answers]",
          "Current KT models have wayu too oversimplistic assumptions, which makes them suffer from volatility:  Among thosse assumptions we have:",
          "Authors introduce a method that uses causal inference to predict outcome via knowledge graphs.\n\nThis is achieved by the additon of an autoencoder model.",
          "The proposed model relies on a set of assumptions:\n\n1- Stable Knowledge Concept Value - Ther is a stable influence that one knowledge concept can have in another.\n\n2. Unconfoundedness - Knowledge concept layout and outcomes are conditionally independent on the data.\n\n3. Separateness: there are 3 sets of variables: Confounding variables (X), Adjustment Variables (Z) and Irrelevant Variables (I) ",
          "BKT, PFA, BKT+FSA, DKVMN, DKT, DKT+, Causal Inference KT",
          "5-Fold Cross-Validation",
          "ASSIST09\n{AUC: 0.833 -  Causal Inference KT, F1-Score: 0.841 - Causal Inference KT}\n\nASSIST15\n{AUC: 0.778 -  Causal Inference KT, F1-Score: 0.840 - Causal Inference KT}\n\nStatics\n{AUC: 0.841 -  Causal Inference KT, F1-Score: 0.909 - Causal Inference KT}\n\nSimulated\n{AUC: 0.826 -  DKT+, F1-Score: 0.796 - DKT+}\n",
          "The main distinction between this model and traditional DKT is the inclusion of restrictions of causal inference that enrich the feature set. \n\nResults show that, indeed, the inclusion of these restrictions make predictions a lot more stable than standard approaches in real datasets.",
          "Does not seem to be effective in smaller sequences of answers - highlighted by the performance on the Synthetic dataset.\n\nNo measurement of additional data sources."
        ]
      ],
      "index": 6
    }
